2.4.3 Constrained Solution
If a liquidity constraint requiring b â‰¥ 0 is ever to be relevant, it must be relevant at
the lowest possible level of market resources, mt = 1, which obtains for a consumer
who enters period t with bt = 0. The constraint is â€˜relevantâ€™ if it prevents the
choice that would otherwise be optimal; at mt = 1 the constraint is relevant if the
marginal utility from spending all of todayâ€™s resources ct = mt = 1, exceeds the
