2.11.2 The WRIC
The â€˜weaknessâ€™ of the additional requirement for contraction, the weak RIC, can
be seen by asking â€˜under what circumstances would the FVAC hold but the
WRIC fail?â€™ Algebraically, the requirement is
Î²Î“1âˆ’Ï Ïˆ 1âˆ’Ï < 1 < (â„˜Î²)1/Ï /R1âˆ’1/Ï .

(42)

If there were no conceivable parameter values that could satisfy both of these
inequalities, the WRIC would have no force; it would be redundant. And if we
require R â‰¥ 1, the WRIC is indeed redundant because now Î² < 1 < RÏâˆ’1 , so that
the RIC (and WRIC) must hold.
But neither theory nor evidence demands that we assume R â‰¥ 1. We can
therefore approach the question of the WRICâ€™s relevance by asking just how low
R must be for the condition to be relevant. Suppose for illustration that Ï = 2,
Ïˆ 1âˆ’Ï = 1.01, Î“1âˆ’Ï = 1.01âˆ’1 and â„˜ = 0.10. In that case (42) reduces to
Î² < 1 < (0.1Î²/R)1/2
but since Î² < 1 by assumption, the binding requirement is that
R < Î²/10
so that for example if Î² = 0.96 we would need R < 0.096 (that is, a perpetual
riskfree rate of return of worse than -90 percent a year) in order for the WRIC to
bind. The relevance of the WRIC is indeed â€œWeak.â€
Perhaps the best way of thinking about this is to note that the space of parameter values for which the WRIC is relevant shrinks out of existence as â„˜ â†’ 0,
which section 2.10 showed was the precise limiting condition under which behavior
becomes arbitrarily close to the liquidity constrained solution (in the absence of
other risks). On the other hand, when â„˜ = 1, the consumer has no noncapital
income (so that the FHWC holds) and with â„˜ = 1 the WRIC is identical to the
RIC; but the RIC is the only condition required for a solution to exist for a perfect
foresight consumer with no noncapital income. Thus the WRIC forms a sort of
â€˜bridgeâ€™ between the liquidity constrained and the unconstrained problems as â„˜
moves from 0 to 1.

