3.3 There Exists Exactly One Target Cash-on-Hand Ratio, which
is Stable
We now prove the existence of a target cash-on-hand-to-income ratio mÌŒ towards
which an agentâ€™s m expects to move. (The âˆ¨ accent is meant to invoke the fact
that this is the value that other mâ€™s â€˜point to.â€™) We state the necessary conditions
for the existence of mÌŒ and its properties in the following theorem.
Theorem 2. For the problem defined in section 2.1, if the GIC (31), and WRIC
(37), then there exists a unique cash-on-hand-to-income ratio mÌŒ > 0 such that
Et [mt+1 /mt ] = 1 if mt = mÌŒ.

(46)

Moreover, mÌŒ is stable in the sense that
âˆ€mt âˆˆ (0, mÌŒ), Et [mt+1 ] > mt
âˆ€mt âˆˆ (mÌŒ, âˆ), Et [mt+1 ] < mt .

(47)

The elements of the proof are:
â€¢ Existence and continuity of Et [mt+1 /mt ]
â€¢ Existence of a point where Et [mt+1 /mt ] = 1
â€¢ Et [mt+1 ] âˆ’ mt is monotonically decreasing
3.3.1 Existence and Continuity of Et [mt+1 /mt ].
The consumption function exists because we have imposed the conditions (the
WRIC and FVAC) that theorem 1 establishes are sufficient for its existence. (Indeed, Appendix C shows that c(m) is not just continuous, but twice continuously
differentiable.)
Section 2.7 shows that for all t, atâˆ’1 = mtâˆ’1 âˆ’ ctâˆ’1 > 0. Since mt = atâˆ’1 Rt + yt ,
even if yt takes on its minimum value of 0, atâˆ’1 Rt > 0, since both atâˆ’1 and
Rt are strictly positive under our foregoing assumptions. With mt > 0, the ratio
Et [mt+1 /mt ] inherits continuity (and, for that matter, continuous differentiability)
from the consumption function.

